From 11149366a2ed5e669477f1aa2da46818af178b7b Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
Date: Fri, 17 Jul 2026 22:38:42 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 1/8] futex: Replay the wakeup consumed by a robust waiter
 killed before acquiring

A robust futex unlock stores 0 over the whole futex value - wiping
FUTEX_WAITERS - and wakes a single waiter. That wakeup is a one-shot
notification: the protocol relies on its recipient to either acquire
the futex (and eventually unlock while aware of the remaining
contention) or re-arm FUTEX_WAITERS before sleeping again.

If the woken waiter is killed before it can do either, and a third
task re-acquired the futex through the uncontended fast path in the
meantime, the notification is lost: the exit time robust list walk
finds the waiter's armed list_op_pending, reads a futex value owned by
a live task and - correctly - leaves the futex value alone, but it
also discards the wakeup. The new owner sees no FUTEX_WAITERS when it
unlocks and wakes nobody. The remaining waiters sleep forever behind a
free futex:

  A owns the futex, B and C sleep in FUTEX_WAIT
                                        uval == A | FUTEX_WAITERS
  A robust unlock: store 0, FUTEX_WAKE(1) wakes B
                                        uval == 0
  D fast path acquire: cmpxchg(0 -> D)
                                        uval == D, no FUTEX_WAITERS
  B killed before acting on the wakeup
  B exit walk, pending op: owner D != B -> no action
  D unlock: no FUTEX_WAITERS -> no wake
                                        C sleeps forever

Commit ca16d5bee598 ("futex: Prevent robust futex exit race") set out
to handle exactly this scenario - its comment spells out "a woken up
waiter is killed before it can acquire the futex in user space" - but
only covers it while the futex value is still 0 when the exit walk
runs. If the futex was re-acquired first, the owner mismatch check
discards the pending op, and the consumed wakeup with it. Complete the
handling for the owner mismatch case: when a pending non PI lock
operation of the dying task is discarded because the futex is owned by
someone else and the futex value does not carry FUTEX_WAITERS, wake
one waiter. The futex value is not touched - the owner is alive - and
a spurious wakeup is harmless: woken waiters re-evaluate the futex
value and re-arm FUTEX_WAITERS before sleeping again, which also
repairs the wiped bit for the remaining sleepers.

If FUTEX_WAITERS is set again by the time the walk runs, no wakeup
needs to be replayed: within the protocol the bit is only ever cleared
by an unlock which issues a wakeup (lock attempts and the exit walk
itself preserve it), so an observed FUTEX_WAITERS guarantees a future
wakeup from the live owner's unlock and the chain is already intact.
This also holds when the task which re-armed the bit dies before
sleeping - the bit stays behind either way. This meaning of the bit is
part of the non PI robust futex ABI, not merely libc convention: the
exit walk itself preserves FUTEX_WAITERS when it marks a dead owner's
futex (mval) and issues its own wakeup only when the bit is set, so
the kernel already requires unlock paths to honor an armed bit.

The window was found by model checking the robust futex wait/wake
interactions with TLC. A deterministic selftest is added in the
following patch.

This patch was developed with the assistance of Claude (an AI
assistant by Anthropic); the author reviewed, validated and takes
responsibility for the changes.

Fixes: ca16d5bee598 ("futex: Prevent robust futex exit race")
Signed-off-by: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
---
 kernel/futex/core.c | 24 +++++++++++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 23 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/kernel/futex/core.c b/kernel/futex/core.c
index 179b26e9c934..e1a8772e4d48 100644
--- a/kernel/futex/core.c
+++ b/kernel/futex/core.c
@@ -1025,8 +1025,30 @@ static int handle_futex_death(u32 __user *uaddr, struct task_struct *curr,
 		return 0;
 	}
 
-	if (owner != task_pid_vnr(curr))
+	if (owner != task_pid_vnr(curr)) {
+		/*
+		 * The dying task's pending op may have consumed the wake up
+		 * notification of a robust unlock: woken, then killed before
+		 * it could act on it. The robust unlock wiped the whole
+		 * futex value including FUTEX_WAITERS, so the owner which
+		 * re-acquired the lock afterwards will unlock through the
+		 * uncontended fast path and never wake the remaining
+		 * waiters. Nothing may be modified here - the lock has a
+		 * live owner - but a potential waiter must be woken to keep
+		 * the wake up chain alive. This is not needed once
+		 * FUTEX_WAITERS is re-armed: the bit is only ever cleared
+		 * by an unlock which issues a wake up (lock attempts and
+		 * this walk preserve it), so an observed FUTEX_WAITERS
+		 * guarantees a future wake up from the owner's unlock and
+		 * no wake up was consumed. The woken waiter re-evaluates
+		 * the futex value and re-arms FUTEX_WAITERS before waiting
+		 * again, so a spurious wake up is harmless.
+		 */
+		if (pending_op && !pi && !(uval & FUTEX_WAITERS))
+			futex_wake(uaddr, FLAGS_SIZE_32 | FLAGS_SHARED, NULL, 1,
+				   FUTEX_BITSET_MATCH_ANY);
 		return 0;
+	}
 
 	/*
 	 * Ok, this dying thread is truly holding a futex
-- 
